    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="1060"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1060">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/502</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the German Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BCJHV1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bernstorff</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-23">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 23, 1914</hi>.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 1133]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Referring to your note of the 21st
                        ultimo,<note n="1" xml:id="d1060fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_658">p. 658</ref>
                    </note> stating that your Embassy was in receipt of information to the effect
                    that, on the night of September 30 last, the tug F. B. <hi rend="italic"
                        >Dalzell</hi> put to sea from Pier 6, East River, New York, to carry
                    provisions to the British cruiser <hi rend="italic">Essex</hi>, which was lying
                    off Gedney Channel; that as she came out of Gedney Channel the tug came under
                    the searchlights of the U. S. <persName>S. <hi rend="italic">Florida</hi>
                    </persName>; that the provisions were taken from the tug in boats sent from the
                    Essex; and that the tug <hi rend="italic">G. H. Dalzell</hi> went on a similar
                    errand on the night of October 1, I have the honor to inform you that the
                    Government of the United States has had the matter thoroughly investigated and
                    has not been able to find as yet sufficient evidence showing that the tug F. B.
                    Dalzell has furnished supplies to British warships. If your excellency can
                    supply any evidence bearing on the matter, the Department will be glad to have a
                    further investigation made on the basis of the new information.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
